// C2: Acting Components
instance ControlAlgorithmExecutor : DTDFVocab:ActingComponent [
    base:desc "Executes closed-loop control algorithms based on digital twin-generated insights and real-time feedback to dynamically reconfigure system components via behavioral reconfiguration."
]

instance ResourceAllocationManager : DTDFVocab:ActingComponent [
    base:desc "Manages dynamic allocation of computational and physical resources (e.g., energy, machinery) through closed-loop control enabled by the Digital Twin's predictive analytics."
]

instance ParameterOptimizer : DTDFVocab:ActingComponent [
    base:desc "Adjusts system parameters (e.g., control algorithms, resource allocation) based on simulation results and digital shadow data to improve operational efficiency."
]

// C3: Physical Sensing Components
instance ContextualDataSensor : DTDFVocab:SensingComponent [
    base:desc "Aggregates heterogeneous sensor data (IoT/embedded/industrial) for contextual data trace collection, supporting real-time or near-real-time monitoring of physical system states."
    DTDFVocab:producedData ContextualDataTrace
]

instance OperationalPerformanceSensor : DTDFVocab:SensingComponent [
    base:desc "Monitors operational metrics and environmental parameters to provide aggregated data for performance benchmarking and anomaly detection."
    DTDFVocab:producedData OperationalPerformanceData
]

instance StateTrackingSensor : DTDFVocab:SensingComponent [
    base:desc "Continuously tracks physical system states (health, performance, environmental conditions) via automated data collection mechanisms."
    DTDFVocab:producedData SystemStateData
]

// C4: Physical-to-Virtual Interaction
instance ContextualDataTrace : DTDFVocab:DataTransmitted [
    DTDFVocab:producedFrom ContextualDataSensor
]

instance OperationalPerformanceData : DTDFVocab:DataTransmitted [
    DTDFVocab:producedFrom OperationalPerformanceSensor
]

instance SystemStateData : DTDFVocab:DataTransmitted [
    DTDFVocab:producedFrom StateTrackingSensor
]

// C10: Models/Data
instance FunctionalArchitectureModel : DTDFVocab:Model [
    base:desc "SysML-based functional architecture model defining system decomposition into components and connectors, aligned with RFLP methodology for requirements-to-physics mapping."
    DTDFVocab:inputTo SysMLModelingEnabler
]

instance LogicalBehaviorModel : DTDFVocab:Model [
    base:desc "AADL/MontiArc-based logical behavior model specifying component interfaces, resource modeling, and automata for dynamic system behavior representation."
    DTDFVocab:inputTo ArchitectureDescriptionEnabler
]

instance SimulationBehaviorModel : DTDFVocab:Model [
    base:desc "Simulink-based dynamic system simulation model for control design, behavioral validation, and predictive analytics integration."
    DTDFVocab:inputTo SimulationEnabler
]

instance DigitalShadowData : DTDFVocab:Data [
    base:desc "Aggregated and abstracted raw sensor data traces from physical system, serving as foundational input for digital twin analysis and decision support."
    DTDFVocab:fromData ContextualDataTrace, OperationalPerformanceData, SystemStateData
    DTDFVocab:inputTo DataProcessingEnabler
]

instance AbstractedStateData : DTDFVocab:Data [
    base:desc "Purpose-driven contextualized data derived from digital shadow inputs, enabling multi-tool integration (SysML, Simulink, C++) for comprehensive system analysis."
    DTDFVocab:fromData DigitalShadowData
    DTDFVocab:inputTo ModelIntegrationEnabler
]

// C11: Enablers
instance SysMLModelingEnabler : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "SysML (v1.7) platform enabling functional and logical architecture modeling via Internal Block Diagrams (IBDs) and state machines for system decomposition and behavioral specification."
    DTDFVocab:enables FunctionalArchitectureService, StateTrackingService
]

instance ArchitectureDescriptionEnabler : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "AADL/ACME/MontiArc framework supporting component-connector perspectives, interface modeling, and automata-based behavioral representation for heterogeneous system architectures."
    DTDFVocab:enables LogicalBehaviorService, ResourceManagementService
]

instance SimulationEnabler : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "MathWorks Simulink engine for dynamic system simulation, control design, and behavioral validation, integrated with general-purpose languages (C++, Java) for custom logic execution."
    DTDFVocab:enables PerformanceForecastingService, FaultDetectionService
]

instance DataProcessingEnabler : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "Middleware framework aggregating and abstracting raw digital shadow data for purpose-driven contextualization, ensuring interoperability across heterogeneous tools."
    DTDFVocab:enables DataAggregationService
]

instance ModelIntegrationEnabler : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "SMArDT methodology platform enabling multi-layered digital twin development (requirements, functions, logic, physics) with traceability across abstraction levels."
    DTDFVocab:enables VisualizationService, OptimizationService
]

// C6: Services
instance FunctionalArchitectureService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Provides SysML-based functional decomposition and architecture modeling services for system design validation and requirements engineering."
    DTDFVocab:provides FunctionalDecompositionInsight
]

instance StateTrackingService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Continuously monitors and tracks physical system states (health, performance) via aggregated digital shadow data for real-time decision support."
    DTDFVocab:provides StateTrackingInsight, HealthMonitoringAction
]

instance LogicalBehaviorService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Delivers AADL/MontiArc-based logical behavior modeling services for dynamic system behavior representation and state machine conformance checks."
    DTDFVocab:provides BehavioralAnalysisInsight, StateMachineValidationAction
]

instance ResourceManagementService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Manages dynamic allocation of computational and physical resources (energy, machinery) through closed-loop control enabled by digital twin insights."
    DTDFVocab:provides ResourceAllocationInsight, AllocationOptimizationAction
]

instance PerformanceForecastingService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Provides simulation-based predictive analytics to estimate future system behavior under varying conditions for performance benchmarking."
    DTDFVocab:provides PerformanceTrendInsight, ForecastingValidationAction
]

instance FaultDetectionService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Uses simulation tools (Simulink, C++) to predict failure modes and degradation trends in the physical system for proactive maintenance."
    DTDFVocab:provides FaultPredictionInsight, MaintenanceRecommendationAction
]

instance DataAggregationService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Aggregates and abstracts raw sensor data traces from digital shadows for purpose-driven contextualization and multi-tool integration."
    DTDFVocab:provides DataContextualizationInsight, AggregationValidationAction
]

instance VisualizationService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Renders interactive 3D/4D models and real-time dashboards for spatial-temporal system state visualization and anomaly highlighting."
    DTDFVocab:provides VisualRepresentationInsight, InteractiveAnalysisAction
]

instance OptimizationService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Adjusts system parameters and configurations based on simulation results to improve operational efficiency and resource utilization."
    DTDFVocab:provides OptimizationRecommendationInsight, ParameterAdjustmentAction
]

// C17: Insights/Actions
instance FunctionalDecompositionInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Decomposed functional architecture aligned with system requirements, enabling traceability from functional to physical layers via SysML."
]

instance ArchitectureValidationInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Validation results of logical/physical architecture models against requirements, ensuring conformance to RFLP/OOSEM methodologies."
]

instance StateTrackingInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Continuous monitoring data of physical system states (health, performance) aggregated from digital shadow inputs for real-time analysis."
]

instance HealthMonitoringAction : DTDFVocab:Action [
    base:desc "Automated health monitoring alerts triggered by deviations from expected system states, enabling proactive maintenance."
    DTDFVocab:IsAutomatic true
]

instance BehavioralAnalysisInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Analysis of system behavior via state machines and automata, validating dynamic responses against expected operational profiles."
]

instance StateMachineValidationAction : DTDFVocab:Action [
    base:desc "Automated conformance checks of system state machines against behavioral specifications, identifying deviations in real-time."
    DTDFVocab:IsAutomatic true
]

instance ResourceAllocationInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Dynamic resource allocation recommendations based on current system load and predictive analytics, optimizing energy and machinery utilization."
]

instance AllocationOptimizationAction : DTDFVocab:Action [
    base:desc "Automated reallocation of computational/physical resources to balance system performance under varying operational conditions."
    DTDFVocab:IsAutomatic true
]

instance PerformanceTrendInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Predictive analytics results forecasting system performance trends under different operational scenarios for benchmarking."
]

instance ForecastingValidationAction : DTDFVocab:Action [
    base:desc "Validation of forecasting models against real-time data to ensure accuracy of performance predictions."
    DTDFVocab:IsAutomatic true
]

instance FaultPredictionInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Simulation-based predictions of failure modes and degradation trends, enabling proactive maintenance planning."
]

instance MaintenanceRecommendationAction : DTDFVocab:Action [
    base:desc "Automated maintenance scheduling and component replacement recommendations based on fault prediction insights."
    DTDFVocab:IsAutomatic true
]

instance DataContextualizationInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Contextualized digital shadow data aligned with specific analytical purposes (e.g., monitoring, optimization) for multi-tool integration."
]

instance AggregationValidationAction : DTDFVocab:Action [
    base:desc "Automated validation of data aggregation processes to ensure quality and consistency of contextualized inputs."
    DTDFVocab:IsAutomatic true
]

instance VisualRepresentationInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Interactive 3D/4D visualizations of system states, enabling immersive analysis and spatial-temporal understanding."
]

instance InteractiveAnalysisAction : DTDFVocab:Action [
    base:desc "User-triggered analysis actions enabling exploration of system behavior through interactive visualization tools."
    DTDFVocab:IsAutomatic false
]

instance OptimizationRecommendationInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Parameter tuning recommendations derived from simulation results to improve system efficiency and performance."
]

instance ParameterAdjustmentAction : DTDFVocab:Action [
    base:desc "Automated adjustment of system parameters (e.g., control algorithms) based on optimization insights for real-time performance enhancement."
    DTDFVocab:IsAutomatic true
]

// C12: Environments
instance PhysicalSystemEnvironment : DTDFVocab:Environment [
    base:contains ContextualDataSensor, OperationalPerformanceSensor, StateTrackingSensor, ControlAlgorithmExecutor, ResourceAllocationManager, ParameterOptimizer
]

instance DigitalTwinEnvironment : DTDFVocab:Environment [
    base:contains FunctionalArchitectureModel, LogicalBehaviorModel, SimulationBehaviorModel, DigitalShadowData, AbstractedStateData,
                SysMLModelingEnabler, ArchitectureDescriptionEnabler, SimulationEnabler, DataProcessingEnabler, ModelIntegrationEnabler
]

instance ServiceEnvironment : DTDFVocab:Environment [
    base:contains FunctionalArchitectureService, StateTrackingService, LogicalBehaviorService, ResourceManagementService,
                PerformanceForecastingService, FaultDetectionService, DataAggregationService, VisualizationService, OptimizationService
]

instance virtual_to_physical_interaction : DTDFVocab:VirtualToPhysical [
    base:desc "The **virtual-to-physical interaction** in Digital Twin systems involves **active control flows** from the digital model to physical assets, governed by the following technical constraints and mechanisms:
  - **Command Types**: Not explicitly detailed, but inferred to include **control signals** (e.g., actuation commands, parameter adjustments) derived from simulations, predictive analytics, or real-time optimization algorithms.
  - **Control Message Formats**: Likely structured using **standardized formats** (e.g., OPC UA information models, JSON/XML payloads) to ensure interoperability with physical systems and middleware.
  - **Validation and Authentication**: While not specified, the document implies **security protocols** (e.g., encryption, digital signatures) to validate commands and authenticate sources, though exact mechanisms are not provided.
  - **Feedback Systems**: Not detailed, but the DT’s role as an **active component** suggests **closed-loop control** where physical responses (e.g., sensor feedback) are fed back into the digital model for iterative refinement.
  - **Conflict Resolution**: Not addressed in the document, but implied to rely on **system-level conflict resolution strategies** (e.g., priority-based scheduling, consensus algorithms) if multiple control sources exist.
  - **Command Execution Confirmation**: Not mentioned, but the DT’s **autonomous processing capability** (unlike digital shadows) implies mechanisms to verify command execution (e.g., acknowledgment protocols, status updates from physical systems).

  The document distinguishes DTs from digital shadows by their **bidirectional interaction**, enabling proactive control and optimization of physical systems."
]

instance twinning_time_scale : DTDFVocab:TimeScale [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin system’s temporal aspects are governed by **Model-Based Systems Engineering (MBSE)** methodologies, which require synchronization between physical and digital components across multiple abstraction layers (e.g., requirements, functional architecture, logical architecture, and product/technical layers). Synchronization frequencies are implicitly tied to the **architecture description languages (ADLs)** and **simulation tools** (e.g., SysML IBDs, MontiArc Automaton, or MathWorks Simulink) used for behavioral modeling. Latency requirements are not explicitly quantified in the provided documents, but the system’s temporal granularity is dictated by the **abstraction levels** (e.g., RFLP methodology’s sequential decomposition of Requirements → Functions → Logics → Physics) and the **real-time processing needs** of aggregated contextual data traces (as referenced in the Digital Shadow context). For active Digital Twin components, the **interpretation and processing of incoming data** (e.g., via active components like those mentioned in [35]–[37]) introduces dynamic time scales dependent on the **stakeholder-specific purposes** of data aggregation. No explicit time scales (e.g., Hz, ms, or sampling intervals) are provided, but the system’s temporal behavior is inherently constrained by the **heterogeneous toolchain** (e.g., SysML, Simulink, or general-purpose languages like C++/Java) and their interoperability constraints."
]

instance dt_constellation : DTDFVocab:Constellation [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin system’s orchestration and coordination are framed within a **multi-layered, model-driven architecture** that integrates **architecture description languages (ADLs)** (e.g., MontiArc, SysML IBDs) for structural modeling and **behavioral modeling tools** (e.g., state machines in SysML v1.7, MontiArc Automaton, or Simulink) for dynamic behavior. The **resource management** is implicitly handled through the **abstraction layers** (e.g., RFLP’s sequential decomposition) and the **toolchain heterogeneity**, requiring **interoperability mechanisms** (e.g., data exchange protocols or middleware) to synchronize models across tools. System-wide coordination is achieved via **component-connector frameworks** (e.g., ADLs’ emphasis on interfaces and interconnections) and the **active components** of the Digital Twin (as referenced in [35]–[37]), which process and aggregate data traces. The document does not specify explicit **orchestration patterns** (e.g., microservices, event-driven, or service-oriented architectures) but highlights the need for **stakeholder-integrated perspectives** and **heterogeneous tool integration** as critical coordination challenges."
]

instance life_cycle_stages : DTDFVocab:EvolutionStage [
    base:desc "The lifecycle of a Digital Twin (DT) system is structured through **Model-Based Systems Engineering (MBSE)** methodologies, encompassing multiple abstraction layers: **requirements**, **functional architecture**, **logical architecture**, and **product/technical layers**. Transition management between these stages is facilitated by methodologies such as **RFLP (Requirements, Functions, Logics, Physics)**, **OOSEM**, **SPES**, or **SMArDT**, which systematically decompose system complexity. Lifecycle governance involves integrating heterogeneous stakeholder perspectives and tools, including **architecture description languages (ADLs)** like **ACME**, **AADL**, **MontiArc**, and **SysML Internal Block Diagrams (IBDs)** for component-connector modeling. Behavior modeling is augmented via **SysML state machines (v1.7)** or **MontiArc Automaton**, while detailed simulations are conducted using **MathWorks Simulink** or other specialized tools. Version control and evolution management are implied through iterative refinement across these layers, though explicit frameworks (e.g., Git-based or model-specific versioning) are not detailed in the document."
]

instance fidelity_and_validity_considerations : DTDFVocab:FidelityConsideration [
    base:desc "
The Digital Twin system’s **fidelity and validity** are implicitly addressed through:
- **Model fidelity requirements**: Derived from **multi-layered MBSE abstractions** (requirements → functional/logical → physical layers), ensuring hierarchical consistency across **SysML, ADLs (e.g., AADL), and simulation tools (e.g., Simulink)**.
- **Validation and verification methods**: Not explicitly detailed, but inferred to include **cross-tool validation** (e.g., SysML → Simulink) and **stakeholder-integrated perspectives** [31].
- **Uncertainty sources**: Likely stem from **sensor noise (implied via digital shadow data aggregation)** and **model abstraction gaps** (e.g., between logical and physical layers).
- **Error detection/correction**: No explicit mechanisms mentioned; however, the Digital Twin’s **active components** (unlike passive digital shadows) may incorporate **real-time data processing** to mitigate discrepancies [35]–[37].
- **Quality assurance processes**: Not described, but **purpose-driven data aggregation** (as per the Digital Shadow Reference Model) suggests **contextual validation frameworks** for traceability and consistency."
]

instance dt_technical_connection : DTDFVocab:TechnicalConnection [
    base:desc "The **technical network infrastructure** for Digital Twin systems is not explicitly detailed in the provided documents, but the following inferences can be made based on broader industry practices and context:
  - **Communication Protocols**: Likely includes **real-time protocols** (e.g., OPC UA for industrial interoperability, MQTT for lightweight IoT messaging, or TCP/IP for general-purpose communication).
  - **Network Topology and Architecture**: Not specified, but the document references **heterogeneous stakeholder integration**, suggesting a **hybrid topology** (e.g., cloud-edge-on-premise) with **service-oriented architectures (SOA)** or **microservices** for modularity.
  - **Bandwidth and Latency Requirements**: Not quantified, but the context implies **low-latency requirements** for real-time applications (e.g., <100ms for control loops) and **scalable bandwidth** to handle aggregated sensor data streams.
  - **Reliability and Redundancy Mechanisms**: Not detailed, but implied to include **fault-tolerant designs** (e.g., redundant data paths, failover mechanisms) to ensure continuous operation.
  - **Security Protocols**: Not explicitly mentioned, but the document’s emphasis on **data integrity** (via aggregation/abstraction) suggests **end-to-end encryption** (e.g., TLS) and **access control policies** (e.g., role-based authentication) for network communication.

  The document does not provide specific details on network infrastructure but aligns with **industrial IoT (IIoT) and cyber-physical system (CPS) standards** for DT connectivity."
]

instance dt_hosting_deployment : DTDFVocab:Deployment [
    base:desc "The **deployment infrastructure** for Digital Twin systems is not explicitly detailed in the provided documents, but the following technical aspects can be inferred from the context:
  - **Hosting Platforms**: The document references **heterogeneous stakeholders and perspectives**, suggesting support for **multi-platform deployment models**, including:
     - **Cloud**: For scalable, centralized DT management and analytics (e.g., AWS, Azure, or Google Cloud).
     - **Edge**: For low-latency processing of localized data (e.g., edge computing nodes near physical assets).
     - **On-Premise**: For legacy systems or high-security environments requiring localized control.
  - **Computational and Storage Requirements**: Not quantified, but implied to vary based on system complexity. **High-performance computing (HPC)** may be required for large-scale simulations (e.g., using tools like Simulink or custom C++/Java applications).
  - **Scalability Mechanisms**: Not detailed, but the document’s mention of **MBSE methodologies** (e.g., SysML, ADLs) suggests **modular, component-based architectures** to enable horizontal scaling of DT instances.
  - **Deployment Models Supported**: Likely includes **containerized deployments** (e.g., Docker, Kubernetes) and **virtualized environments** (e.g., VMs) for flexibility, though not explicitly stated.
  - **Availability/Reliability Assurance**: Not specified, but the document’s emphasis on **data aggregation and abstraction** implies **redundant data storage** and **disaster recovery mechanisms** to maintain DT availability.

  The document does not provide specific hardware/software requirements but aligns with **industry best practices** for deploying DTs in **manufacturing and industrial automation** contexts."
]

instance horizontal_integration : DTDFVocab:HoriIntegration [
    base:desc "Horizontal integration in the Digital Twin system is enabled through **heterogeneous toolchain interoperability**, including **Model-Based Systems Engineering (MBSE) languages** (e.g., SysML, ADLs like AADL or MontiArc) and **simulation tools** (e.g., MathWorks Simulink, other simulation methods [29], [30], or general-purpose languages like C++/Java). The system relies on **architecture description languages** to define **component interfaces, connectors, and composition rules**, facilitating integration with external systems via standardized **data exchange protocols** (implicitly assumed but not explicitly named). The document references **dependencies on external systems** through the **Digital Shadow context**, where data traces are aggregated for specific purposes, suggesting integration with **enterprise systems** or **manufacturing data platforms**. However, no specific **interoperability standards** (e.g., OPC UA, ROS, or REST APIs) or **integration patterns** (e.g., API gateways, ESBs, or federated architectures) are detailed. The **scope of integration** is broadened by the need to align **multiple stakeholder perspectives**, as noted in [31], but the technical specifics of horizontal integration remain abstract."
]

instance standardization : DTDFVocab:Standardization [
    base:desc "The document references **industry standards** for Digital Twin development, including **Model-Based Systems Engineering (MBSE) methodologies** (e.g., **SysML** for architecture modeling) and **architecture description languages (ADLs)** like **ACME**, **AADL**, and **MontiArc** for component-connector interoperability. **SysML v1.7** is specified for behavioral modeling (state machines), while **MathWorks Simulink** is implied for simulation interoperability. No explicit **certification frameworks** or **compliance standards** (e.g., ISO/IEC 42010, IEEE 1517) are mentioned, though **interoperability** is addressed via toolchain integration (e.g., SysML + Simulink). The **Digital Shadow Reference Model** (Kritzinger et al.) is cited as a conceptual foundation for data aggregation, but no formal **standardization body** (e.g., OMG, IEC) is referenced."
]

instance security_and_safety_considerations : DTDFVocab:SecuritySafety [
    base:desc "
The Digital Twin system for the MABI MAX 100 serial robot incorporates multiple **safety-critical mechanisms** and **cybersecurity protocols** to ensure operational integrity and threat mitigation. The **safety cell** restricts the maximum working range of the first axis to [-90°, 90°] and enforces a **maximum speed limit of |q̇_max| = 75°/s**, preventing unsafe kinematic excursions. **Fail-safe mechanisms** are embedded in the **dual-encoder sensor arrangement** (motor encoder and secondary encoder behind the gearbox), which enables real-time backlash compensation and positional uncertainty reduction by cross-referencing encoder data. This mitigates mechanical faults (e.g., gear elasticity, friction) that could compromise system stability.

For **cybersecurity**, the robot is controlled via the **Siemens SINUMERIK 840D sl CNC controller**, which enforces **access control mechanisms** through role-based permissions for programming, monitoring, and operational adjustments. The system supports **authentication systems** via secure user logins tied to the controller’s firmware, ensuring unauthorized modifications to trajectory planning or motor parameters are prevented. **Threat mitigation** is implicitly addressed through the controller’s **closed-loop feedback** (position, speed, acceleration inputs/outputs) and **motor current monitoring**, which converts current (I_M) to torque (τ_M) using known motor constants, thereby detecting anomalies in real-time. However, explicit **risk assessment frameworks** (e.g., ISO 27001, IEC 62443) or **data anonymization protocols** for shared datasets are not documented in the provided context."
]